  "prompt": "If Buddhism is not a religion, then what is it?",
  "response": "The classification of Buddhism can vary depending on one's perspective and interpretation. While many people consider Buddhism to be a religion, others see it more as a philosophy, spiritual tradition, or way of life. Here are several ways to understand Buddhism:\n\n1. **Religion**: For many, Buddhism fits within the definition of a religion because it involves practices, rituals, ethical teachings, and a community of followers. It addresses spiritual concerns and offers a path toward enlightenment and liberation from suffering.\n\n2. **Philosophy**: Buddhism can also be viewed as a philosophy because it involves systematic teachings on the nature of reality, existence, and the mind. It encourages rational inquiry and personal introspection to understand and overcome suffering.\n\n3. **Spiritual Tradition**: Some people describe Buddhism as a spiritual tradition because it provides practices aimed at spiritual development and realization, such as meditation, mindfulness, and ethical living.\n\n4. **Way of Life**: Buddhism can be seen as a way of life because it offers practical guidance on how to live ethically and mindfully, with compassion and wisdom, in daily life.\n\nUltimately, the classification depends on individual and cultural perspectives, and Buddhism encompasses elements of all these descriptions. It is multidimensional and can be experienced and interpreted in various ways.",
